  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) efforts date back to the 1920s\n- Initially focused on combating organized crime and tax evasion\n- US Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 was a pivotal early legislative milestone\n\n2. Key Developmental Periods:\n- 1970s-1980s: Growing recognition of money laundering as a serious criminal issue\n- Increased focus on disrupting drug trafficking financial networks\n- Emergence of international cooperation frameworks\n\n3. Major Legislative Landmarks:\n- 1986: US Money Laundering Control Act\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: European Community Money Laundering Directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n4. Global Regulatory Evolution:\n- Increasing international standardization of AML protocols\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Expanded definitions of money laundering activities\n- Stricter penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Contemporary Developments:\n- Growing focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- Increased emphasis on combating terrorist financing\n- More comprehensive international regulatory frameworks\n\nThe legal history reflects progressively more sophisticated approaches to preventing financial crimes.",
